l and contemporary aspects of Russia's naval strategy and capacities.At a time of mounting tensions, which some observers have named the ‘Fourth Battle of the Atlantic’, the book offers an informed and nuanced discussion, taking into account the view from Moscow and how this differs from western perspectives. It sketches a trajectory of Russia’s power at sea and reflects on current capabilities and problems, as well as Moscow’s strategic planning for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSea-powerzRussia (Federation). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAdmiral Kuznetsov.  aCold War.  aFourth Battle of the Atlantic.  aKalibr missile.  aMoskva.  aRussia-Ukraine War.  aRussian Navy.  aRussian naval strategy.  aVladimir Putin.  ahybrid war.  amaritime theory.  asea power.1 aConnolly, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnstone, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKofman, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonaghan, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonaghan, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetersen, Michael B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStack, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTill, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616879540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526168795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978152